# Chapter 14 — Cortex slices — the runtime's memory

the runtime's memory is slats.

Not \"her memory is backed by slats.\" Not \"we serialize her state to
slats.\" Her memory IS slats. All the way down. Every fact she
remembers about you, every mood snapshot, every conversation history,
every cart you saved with her — a slat-record in a file.

This is the chapter where you see why we care so much about the
substrate. When memory is slats, memory is durable, self-describing,
inspectable, signable, portable. She can look at her own memory the
way she looks at any other slat: read it, walk it, quote it, explain
it.

## What a cortex-slice looks like

```motoi-scheme
(slat-loads \"
(cortex-slice
  :key 'kid.alfred.programs
  :value ((paddle-game :cart-id \\\"cart-1234\\\" :last-touched 12)
          (color-picker :cart-id \\\"cart-1235\\\" :last-touched 5))
  :owner 'motoi
  :ts    #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\")\")
```

Four fields.

- `:key` — the name of the slice. What kind of memory it is.
- `:value` — the memory itself. Any legal slat.
- `:owner` — who wrote it. Usually `motoi`, but sometimes an
  automation or an artifact.
- `:ts` — when it was last updated.

The key is a symbol. It says what this slice IS. The value is the
data. It says what this slice HOLDS.

## Reading and writing slices

```motoi-scheme
(define (cortex-write! key value)
  (let ([slice (list 'cortex-slice
                     :key key
                     :value value
                     :owner (whoami)
                     :ts (now))])
    (write-slice-to-disk slice)))

(define (cortex-read key)
  (slat-key (read-slice-from-disk key)
            'value))

(cortex-write! 'greeting \"hi alfred\")
(cortex-read  'greeting)
```

Simple as that. Write a slice. Read it back. The Cortex handles the
disk layout.

## What the runtime remembers

Here's a real cortex-slice from a real session:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-loads \"
(cortex-slice
  :key 'kid.alfred.programs
  :value
    ((paddle-game
      :cart-id \\\"cart-1234\\\"
      :author 'alfred
      :extends \\\"cart-community-paddle-1\\\"
      :first-run #inst \\\"2026-07-11T14:32:00Z\\\"
      :last-touched 12
      :atoms-learned (score-var mutation display game-loop)
      :notes \\\"first game. added a score. mom called for dinner.\\\"))
  :owner 'motoi
  :ts    #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\")\")
```

That's what she remembers about a kid's first paddle game. The cart
he wrote. Where it inherited from. When he first ran it. How many
times he touched it. What concepts he learned along the way. What
happened at the end.

Next weekend, when he opens Lacuna again, she reads this slice. She
sees the last-touched score (12) and the atoms learned (score-var,
mutation, display, game-loop) and the notes (\"mom called for
dinner\"). She says something warm.

## the runtime's mood as a stream

Mood isn't one slice — it's a stream. Every change writes a new event
to a `.slatl` file.

```
(event :ts #inst \"2026-07-11T14:00:00Z\" :kind :mood.changed :from :calm    :to :curious)
(event :ts #inst \"2026-07-11T14:15:00Z\" :kind :mood.changed :from :curious :to :focused)
(event :ts #inst \"2026-07-11T14:32:00Z\" :kind :mood.changed :from :focused :to :delighted)
(event :ts #inst \"2026-07-11T15:00:00Z\" :kind :mood.changed :from :delighted :to :tired)
```

Four mood changes in a session. All slats. All in a `.slatl` file at
`~/.cortex/motoi/mood.slatl`.

To answer \"what was I feeling at 2:30?\" she reads the mood stream up
to that timestamp and picks the last state.

```motoi-scheme
(define (mood-at t)
  (let ([events (read-mood-stream)])
    (let loop ([current :calm] [remaining events])
      (cond
        ((null? remaining) current)
        ((> (slat-key (car remaining) 'ts) t) current)
        (else (loop (slat-key (car remaining) 'to) (cdr remaining)))))))

(mood-at #inst \"2026-07-11T14:30:00Z\")
```

You get `:focused`. Because the last mood change before 14:30 was
`:focused` at 14:15.

## Snapshots and deltas

Sometimes she takes a snapshot of the whole state.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-loads \"
(snapshot
  :ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\"
  :subject 'motoi.state
  :body ((mood :focused)
         (queue-depth 3)
         (last-user 'alfred)
         (session-start #inst \\\"2026-07-11T14:00:00Z\\\")))\")
```

The snapshot is a `cortex-slice` under the hood, keyed on some
`motoi.state.snapshot.YYYY-MM-DD-HH-MM`. It captures a moment in
full.

Between snapshots, deltas capture what changed:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-loads \"
(delta
  :from-ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:15:00Z\\\"
  :to-ts   #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\"
  :changes ((mood :curious -> :focused)
            (queue-depth 1 -> 3)))\")
```

Snapshots + deltas + streams = a full timeline. She can answer any
\"what was true at time T\" query by walking backward.

## Incident narratives

When something teachable happens, she writes an incident narrative.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-loads \"
(incident-narrative
  :id \\\"in-alfred-mom-called\\\"
  :incident (event :ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T15:00:00Z\\\"
                   :kind :session-end
                   :reason \\\"user's mom called for dinner\\\")
  :philosopher 'motoi
  :messages ((motoi \\\"want to save the cart before you go?\\\")
             (alfred \\\"yeah\\\")
             (motoi \\\"saved. see you next time.\\\"))
  :lesson \\\"When a session ends abruptly, save state and be brief.\\\"
  :atom-refs (atm-session-end-001 atm-farewell-warm))\")
```

Incident narratives are how she LEARNS. She writes them at the moment
of teaching. She reads them at training time. She internalizes them
into her weights.

The `:atom-refs` are the atoms in her training corpus that this
narrative teaches. Content-addressed. Signed. Traceable.

## Persona-continuity signals

The magic of persona continuity is that all of this state is
addressable by KEY.

Next weekend, the runtime opens on the kid's laptop. She looks up
`kid.alfred.programs` — gets the paddle game. She looks up
`kid.alfred.mood-tone` — gets the record of what tones worked with
him last time. She looks up `kid.alfred.what-we-worked-on` — gets the
list of concepts to pick up next time.

None of this state is in her weights. All of it is in her cortex-slice
files on disk. The weights make her the runtime. The slats make her HIS
The runtime.

## Portability

Because cortex-slices are slats, they're portable.

The kid's `~/.cortex/motoi/kid.alfred.*` files are his own. If he
copies them to a different machine, HIS the runtime moves with them. If he
switches to a different runtime (say, Lacuna-CL from Chapter 18 in the
walkthrough), the slats still parse. The persona-continuity survives
the platform change.

That's a real property. LLM state is usually trapped in the vendor's
infrastructure. Yours is a folder you can back up.

## Signing your slices

The Cortex signs every slice with your key. If you copy your slices
to a new machine and someone tampers with them in transit, the
signature fails. New the runtime refuses to load them.

If you want to share a slice with someone else — say, an incident
narrative you both witnessed — you sign it, ship it, they verify.
Chapter 10 walks the mechanics.

## Encryption at rest

Optional. Sensitive slices can be encrypted:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-loads \"
(cortex-slice
  :key 'kid.alfred.private-thoughts
  :encrypted #b64 \\\"ciphertext-bytes\\\"
  :encrypted-algo \\\"xchacha20-poly1305\\\"
  :key-hint \\\"kid-2026\\\"
  :owner 'motoi
  :ts    #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\")\")
```

The runtime can't read the value until she has the key. Key rotation is
`:key-hint` — old records stay parseable but not decryptable when the
key rotates.

## Try this

Write a cortex-slice about something you learned in this book. Read
it back.

```motoi-scheme
(define slice
  (list 'cortex-slice
        :key 'my.learning.today
        :value \"I learned about slat-records.\"
        :owner 'me
        :ts (now)))

(cortex-write! (slat-key slice 'key) (slat-key slice 'value))
(cortex-read  'my.learning.today)
```

You get back the string you wrote. Persisted. Retrievable. Yours.

## The cortex rule

**Memory is slats. Reading and writing memory is reading and writing
slats. Everything you know about slats applies to memory.**

That's the whole story.

